Qualifying standards for World Maters Championships 2019

Marianne, Friedrich, David, Les

06 October 2018

1 Trend in participation in IWF world championships across years

The number of participants has been steadily increasing over the years with an explosion of the number of participants in recent years. It is expected that this explosion will continue.

The increase in women participation has been seen in US National competitions for a while. Among the younger age groups women outnumbered men at the IWF 2018 in Barcelona.

Trend in number of participants

2 Bodyweight distribution

The middle weight classes have the largest number of lifters.

Due the body weight and age distributions it is reasonable to calculate qualifying totals [in kg] based on SMF cutoff values calculated for the top body weight in each weight class and an age in the middle of each age class (e.g. 37, 42, etc)

A decision needs to be made for the heaviest weight classes. In this document the reference weight was 120 kg for men and 100kg for women.

This indicates that the most pressure is in the younger age groups in the middle body weight categories.

3 SMF cutoffs, qualifying totals, and number of participants

Comment: A Poisson regression model to predict the number of lifters in each age/weight category showed that of the three predictors age, weight, and SMF, only the age group plays a statistically significant role. That means there are more lifters in the younger age groups. The larger numbers of the middle body weight classes seen in the younger age groups are too few cells, so that body weight did not reach statistical significance to predict the number of lifters. Thus is would be acceptable to focus on qualifying standards by age category only.

3.2 Comparisons of scenarios for SMF cutpoints

The median SMF for each age class of the current world championships SMF qualifying standards was taken to arrive at a SMF qualifying standard currently used at the worlds.

SMF cutpoints [men]
agecat M35 M40 M45 M50 M55 M60 M65 M70 M75 M80+
world 278 280 285 280 274 270 261 236 247 223
AC 290 290 285 280 275 270 265 260 255 250
SMF cutpoints [women]
agecat W35 W40 W45 W50 W55 W60 W65 W70 W75 W80+
world 141 142 138 134 132 131 130 136 136 136
AC 170 170 160 155 150 145 145 145 145 145

The SMF standard for men was proposed in order to stay close to the current standard, but increase for the younger age groups due to the large number of participants. The standards were raised a small amount in the older age groups for consistency ages 65 and up.

The proposed SMF standard for women accounts for the exploding participation of women, especially in the younger age groups. The current standard for women is unusually low. Thus the choice for the younger age groups was driven by the number of participants, and then linearly decreased for older ages.

4 Number of qualifying athletes

In the following the number of qualifying athletes are calculated according to different schemes of qualifying totals based on the proposed SMF standard However the number appears lower, since 5 to 8% of the participants did not total.

When determining targets for registration limits, the following points need to be considered.

  1. Registration limit: About 8 to 16% of athletes who register are not able to participate. Thus a target of 700 participants at the world championships could mean a target of 756 to 812 participants for registrations. This could also be differentiated for gender. There tend to be fewer no-shows for women than for men.

  2. SMF/QT standards: The proportion of athletes who do not total are 5 to 8%. These are not included in the numbers below, even though they may qualify with the new qualifying standards. Thus when deciding on a heme that should result in 700 athletes, for example, it would be advisable to choose a target of 644 to 665 athletes

At the IWF 2016 (GER) there were 552 men with a total and 192 women with a total.

At the IWF 2018 (ESP) there were 395 men with a total and 337 women with a total.

With the proposed qualifying standards the estimated number of future participants is 452 men (2016 data) and 256 women (2018 data) for a total of 708 weightlifters. Since this is based on those with a total >0, an estimated total number is 765 participants. However, it can be expected that the number of qualfied athletes continues to rise especially in the 35-44 age group.
